['Based on the ideas and physical background of a nonlinear harmonic oscillator, the acceleration \\( y \\) can be modeled as a function of time \\( x_0 \\), position \\( x_1 \\), and velocity \\( x_2 \\) with terms representing:\n\n- A constant offset (bias)\n- Linear dependence on time (external forcing or drift)\n- Linear restoring force proportional to position (Hooke\'s law)\n- Cubic nonlinear stiffness term proportional to \\( x_1^3 \\)\n- Linear damping proportional to velocity\n\nThis leads to a skeleton like:\n\n\\[\ny = p_0 + p_1 x_0 + p_2 x_1 + p_3 x_1^3 + p_4 x_2\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\(p_0\\) is a constant offset,\n- \\(p_1\\) captures linear time dependence,\n- \\(p_2\\) is the linear stiffness coefficient,\n- \\(p_3\\) is the nonlinear stiffness coefficient,\n- \\(p_4\\) is the damping coefficient.\n\n---\n\nHere is an implementation of `equation_v1` reflecting this structure:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, x2: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    Calculates acceleration y for a nonlinear harmonic oscillator given:\n    - x0: time\n    - x1: position at time t\n    - x2: velocity at time t\n\n    Uses parameters for constant offset, linear time term, linear and cubic position terms,\n    and linear velocity term (damping).\n    \n    Parameters:\n        params (np.ndarray): array of parameters [p0, p1, p2, p3, p4]\n    \n    Returns:\n        y (np.ndarray): acceleration values\n    """\n    return (\n        params[0]               # constant offset\n        + params[1] * x0       # linear in time\n        + params[2] * x1       # linear restoring force\n        + params[3] * (x1 ** 3)  # nonlinear stiffness cubic term\n        + params[4] * x2       # damping term proportional to velocity\n    )\n```\n\nThis skeleton can be extended by adding more terms if needed but captures the essential physics described in your ideas.', 'Based on the ideas and physical background of a nonlinear harmonic oscillator, the acceleration \\( y \\) (dependent variable) can be modeled as a function of time \\( x_0 \\), position \\( x_1 \\), and velocity \\( x_2 \\). The typical form includes:\n\n- A constant term (bias)\n- A linear term in time (to capture any explicit time dependence)\n- A linear restoring force term proportional to position (\\(x_1\\)) with negative sign\n- A nonlinear restoring force term proportional to the cube of position (\\(x_1^3\\)) for nonlinear stiffness\n- A damping term proportional to velocity (\\(x_2\\)) with negative sign\n\nThis leads to a skeleton like:\n\n\\[\ny = p_0 + p_1 x_0 + p_2 x_1 + p_3 x_1^3 + p_4 x_2\n\\]\n\nwhere typically \\(p_2 < 0\\) (restoring force), \\(p_3 < 0\\) or positive depending on hardening/softening nonlinearity, and \\(p_4 < 0\\) (damping).\n\n---\n\nHere is an implementation of `equation_v1` reflecting this skeleton:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, x2: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """\n    Improved version of equation_v0 including nonlinear terms.\n\n    y = params[0] + params[1]*x0 + params[2]*x1 + params[3]*x1**3 + params[4]*x2\n\n    Parameters:\n    - x0: time array\n    - x1: position array at time t\n    - x2: velocity array at time t\n    - params: trainable coefficients (at least length 5)\n\n    Returns:\n    - y: acceleration array\n    """\n    return (\n        params[0] \n        + params[1] * x0 \n        + params[2] * x1 \n        + params[3] * (x1 ** 3) \n        + params[4] * x2\n    )\n```\n\n---\n\nThis function skeleton captures the essential physics of a nonlinear oscillator with damping and possible external/time-dependent forcing. You can extend it by adding higher order terms or cross terms if needed.', '```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, x2: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    This function models the acceleration y of a nonlinear harmonic oscillator,\n    given time (x0), position (x1), and velocity (x2).\n\n    The model includes:\n    - A constant term (params[0])\n    - Linear time dependence (params[1] * x0)\n    - Linear restoring force term proportional to position (params[2] * x1)\n    - Nonlinear stiffness term proportional to cubic position (params[3] * x1**3)\n    - Damping term proportional to velocity (params[4] * x2)\n\n    Parameters:\n        x0 (np.ndarray): Time variable\n        x1 (np.ndarray): Position at time t\n        x2 (np.ndarray): Velocity at time t\n        params (np.ndarray): Array of parameters [p0, p1, ..., p9]\n\n    Returns:\n        np.ndarray: Computed acceleration y\n    """\n    return (\n        params[0]\n        + params[1] * x0\n        + params[2] * x1\n        + params[3] * x1**3\n        + params[4] * x2\n    )\n```\n\n---\n\n### Explanation:\n\n- `params[0]`: constant offset or bias term.\n- `params[1]*x0`: linear dependence on time — can represent external forcing or drift.\n- `params[2]*x1`: linear restoring force term — typical in harmonic oscillators.\n- `params[3]*x1**3`: nonlinear stiffness term — captures anharmonicity/nonlinearity.\n- `params[4]*x2`: damping proportional to velocity.\n\nThis skeleton matches the physical intuition for a nonlinear damped oscillator with possible external forcing. Additional parameters (`params[5:]`) can be used later if needed for more complex terms.', 'Based on the ideas and physical background of a nonlinear harmonic oscillator, the acceleration \\( y \\) can be modeled as a combination of:\n\n- A constant term (bias)\n- A linear term in time \\( x_0 \\) (to capture any explicit time dependence)\n- A linear term in position \\( x_1 \\) (restoring force, typically negative stiffness)\n- A cubic term in position \\( x_1^3 \\) (nonlinear stiffness)\n- A linear term in velocity \\( x_2 \\) (damping)\n\nThis matches the classical Duffing oscillator form:\n\n\\[\ny = a_0 + a_1 x_0 + a_2 x_1 + a_3 x_1^3 + a_4 x_2\n\\]\n\nwhere parameters \\(a_i\\) are trainable coefficients.\n\n---\n\nHere is the implementation of `equation_v1` reflecting this skeleton:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, x2: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    Models acceleration y as:\n    y = params[0] + params[1]*x0 + params[2]*x1 + params[3]*x1**3 + params[4]*x2\n\n    Parameters:\n    - x0: time\n    - x1: position at time t\n    - x2: velocity at time t\n    - params: array of parameters [a0, a1, a2, a3, a4,...]\n\n    Returns:\n    - y: acceleration at time t\n    """\n    return (\n        params[0] \n        + params[1] * x0 \n        + params[2] * x1 \n        + params[3] * (x1 ** 3) \n        + params[4] * x2\n    )\n```\n\n---\n\nThis function skeleton captures the essential physics of nonlinear oscillators with damping and nonlinear restoring forces. You can extend it by adding higher order terms or other nonlinearities if needed.']
